# Nouns Reference Content

Noun declensions by gender and case - how Greek nouns change their endings.

## Purpose

Show how Greek nouns decline according to gender, case, and number. The ending patterns reveal the underlying system.

## Key Insight

Greek nouns change their endings to show grammatical function (case) and number. Learn the pattern by gender and the system becomes predictable.

---

## Gender Detection (Hero Element)

<quick-reference name="gender-hints">
<title>Spot gender by ending</title>

| Gender    | Common Endings | Tip |
|-----------|----------------|-----|
| Masculine | -ος, -ας, -ης, -ές | Most words for male people |
| Feminine  | -α, -η, -ση/-ξη | Female people, abstract nouns (-η) |
| Neuter    | -ο, -ι, -μα | Diminutives (-ι, -άκι), result nouns (-μα) |

</quick-reference>

---

## Core Insight

<insight>
Greek nouns change their endings to show:
- **Case**: nominative (subject), accusative (object), genitive (possession)
- **Number**: singular / plural

The article changes along with the noun and helps identify the gender.
</insight>

